<h2>Italian Immigration to Canada</h2>

<p>
Italian immigrants arrived in Canada and the United States in two waves during 
the Twentieth Century, primarily driven by economic opportunities. The first wave was between 
the early 1900s and World War I. The second wave was primarly after World War II.
</p>

<p>
In the first wave of Italian migration to Canada Italian migrants immigrated in search of labour. Immigrants were drawn by opportunities to construct
  transcontinental railroads, grain elevators, work in mines, and work as tradesmen.  
  Immigrants worked in harsh and dangerous condtions while also facing discrimination.
</p>

<p>
Many of the 60,000 Italian Immigrants settled in Ontario. As postions were often seasonal and harsh immigrants often moved back to Italy or established roots in Canada. Many families looking to feed their families moved to cities like Windsor.
 Windsor was ideal due to its proximity to Detroit, and as the city's automotive and construction industries grew, so did the Italian population.
</p>

<p>
Although many worked in factories or construction, some began their businesses. As many Italians moved back to Italy, some stayed in cities like Windsor in search of economic opportunities. A culture of hard work, dedication, and commitment to family flourished and quickly became pillars of business success.
</p>

